# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: walden
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:walden/a-different-drummer-novel] The novel gives background and context to Caliban's act across a dozen chapters, each told from the perspective of different white townspersons.
[src:walden/a-different-drummer-novel] The original edition starts with an extended dedication (to the author's mother, his father and to "MSL"), and an epigraph (two separate stanzas from *Walden* by Henry David Thoreau, one of which includes the title of the book).
[src:walden/a-different-drummer-novel] The novel is divided into 11 titled chapters.
[src:walden/a-different-drummer-novel] The narrative is told from the viewpoint of the town's white inhabitants.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] "**A Plea for Captain John Brown**" is an essay by Henry David Thoreau, based on a speech he first delivered to an audience at Concord, Massachusetts, on October 30, 1859, two weeks after John Brown's raid on Harpers Ferry, and repeated several times before Brown's execution on December 2, 1859.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] It was later published as a part of *Echoes of Harper's Ferry* in 1860.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] John Brown, a radical abolitionist, and 21 other men seized the Federal armory at Harper's Ferry, the holding place for approximately 100,000 rifles and muskets, hoping to arm slaves and create a violent rebellion against the South.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] After 36 hours, the revolt was suppressed by Federal forces led by Robert E.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] The raid resulted in thirteen deaths: twelve rebels and one U.S.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Brown himself, after being found guilty of murder, treason, and inciting a slave insurrection, was hanged on December 2, 1859.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Although largely called a failure at the time, the raid and Brown's subsequent execution impelled the American Civil War.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Thoreau's essay espoused John Brown and his fight for abolition.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] In opposition with popular opinion of the time – Thoreau vehemently refuted the claims of newspapers and his fellow countrymen who characterized Brown as foolish and insane – he painted a portrait of a peerless man whose embrace of a cause was unparalleled.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Brown's commitment to justice and adherence to the United States Constitution forced him to fight state-sponsored injustice, one he was only affected by in spirit.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] A unique man, Thoreau proclaimed in admiration, Brown was highly moral and humane.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Independent, "under the auspices of John Brown and nobody else", and direct of speech, Brown instilled fear, which he attributed to a lack of cause, into large groups of men who supported slavery.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Incomparable to man, Thoreau likens Brown's execution – he states that he regards Brown as dead before his actual death – to Christ's crucifixion at the hands of Pontius Pilate, with whom he compares the American government.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Thoreau vents at the scores of Americans who have voiced their displeasure and scorn for John Brown.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] The same people, Thoreau says, can't relate to Brown because of their concrete stances and "dead" existences; they are truly not living, only a handful of men have lived.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Thoreau also criticizes contemporary Christians, who say their prayers and then go to sleep aware of injustice but doing nothing to change it.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Similarly, Thoreau states those who believe Brown threw his life away and died as a fool, are themselves fools.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Brown gave his life for justice, not for material gains, and was completely sane, perhaps more so than any other human being.
[src:walden/a-plea-for-captain-john-brown] Rebutting the arguments based on the small number of rebels, Thoreau responds "when were the good and the brave ever in a majority?" Thoreau also points out the irony of *The Liberator*, an abolitionist newspaper, labeling Brown's actions as misguided.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] "**A Walk to Wachusett**" is an 1843 essay written by Henry David Thoreau recounting an excursion he took with a companion, Richard Fuller, from Concord, Massachusetts to the summit of Mount Wachusett located in Princeton, Massachusetts.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] Their journey, by foot, began on July 19, 1842.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] Traveling through Acton, Stow, Bolton, Lancaster and Sterling, they arrived in West Sterling by sunset and lodged overnight at a local inn, most likely the Milton Buss Inn and Tavern.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] Reaching the summit the following day, the pair had traveled a distance of approximately 34 miles (55 km).
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] Their time on the summit was spent exploring, relaxing and pondering the landscape and its inhabitants.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] The signature line of the essay, "Wachusett is, in fact, the observatory of the state", was rewritten from a similar line by Princeton native Charles Theodore Russell in his book *History of Princeton* published in 1838.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] First published in the January 1843 issue of *The Boston Miscellany*, this was perhaps the first of Thoreau's works describing excursions he took over the years.
[src:walden/a-walk-to-wachusett] Later trips, including a return to Wachusett in October 1854 as well as trips to Maine, New Hampshire and Vermont, are documented in his journals.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] On July 4, 1845, Henry David Thoreau moved to a small home he assembled at Walden Pond and lived there for two years, two months, and two days.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] During his time there, he completed the first draft of *A Week on the Concord and Merrimack Rivers*.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] He was unable to find a publisher, however, and therefore had it printed at his own expense.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] Published in 1849, it was Thoreau's first book and it cost him several hundred dollars, though only 219 copies sold.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] By 1853, the printer refused to store the unsold copies and returned 706 of them to Thoreau, who noted at the time, "I have now a library of nearly nine hundred volumes, over seven hundred of which I wrote myself".
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] In 1842, Thoreau sold the *Musketaquid*, the boat he used for his journey, to Nathaniel Hawthorne for $7 and a rowing lesson.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] Hawthorne, then living at The Old Manse, renamed the boat *Pond Lily* but was disappointed he was not able to operate the boat as easily as Thoreau, for whom it seemed "as docile as a trained steed".
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] A slightly revised version of *A Week on the Concord and Merrimack Rivers*, based on corrections Thoreau had made himself, was published in 1868, six years after his death.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] It received only two contemporary reviews.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] *The Athenæum* described it as one of the "worst offshoots of Carlyle and Emerson." *The Westminster Review* also took issue with its style, though in all felt that "the book is an agreeable book." Thoreau had sent a copy to James Anthony Froude, who wrote back, "In your book . . .
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] An 1853 short story by Herman Melville, "Cock-A-Doodle-Doo!", is interpreted as a satire of Thoreau's book.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] The French composer Robert Piéchaud (born 1969) wrote *The River* (2016), a wind quintet which freely follows Thoreau's work.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] An additional voice part is found in the last movement, setting *All Things Are Current Found*, the last poem of the book.
[src:walden/a-week-on-the-concord-and-merrimack-rivers] John McPhee recreated Thoreau's journey in a canoe starting August 31, 2003, and wrote about it in "Paddling After Henry David Thoreau".
[src:walden/affluenza] The word is thought to have been first used in 1908, and to have been adopted for its most common current usage in California in 1973.
[src:walden/affluenza] It was also used by John Levy, executive director of the C.G.
[src:walden/affluenza] Jung Institute in San Francisco in 1984 to describe the lack of motivation that could dog wealthy people.
[src:walden/affluenza] It was popularized in 1997 with a PBS documentary of the same name and the subsequent book *Affluenza: The All-Consuming Epidemic* (2001, revised in 2005, 2014).
[src:walden/affluenza] These works define affluenza as "a painful, contagious, socially transmitted condition of overload, debt, anxiety, and waste resulting from the dogged pursuit of more".
[src:walden/affluenza] A more informal definition of the term describes it as "a quasi-illness caused by guilt for one's own socio-economic superiority".
[src:walden/affluenza] The term "affluenza" has also been used to refer to an inability to understand the consequences of one's actions because of financial privilege, as described in discussions of the psychological effects of inherited wealth.
[src:walden/affluenza] The term "affluenza" was re-popularized in 2013 with the arrest of Ethan Couch, a wealthy Texas teen, for driving while intoxicated and killing four pedestrians and injuring several others.
[src:walden/affluenza] Testimony from a psychologist in court referred to Couch as having a case of affluenza, sparking a media frenzy and victim family outrage.
[src:walden/affluenza] The psychologist testified during the sentencing phase as a part of mitigation of penalty, not, as was reported, as a defence to the charge at trial.
[src:walden/affluenza] The term has been further popularized by the case of Ontario billionaire Marco Muzzo, who, like Couch, was arrested for driving while intoxicated, causing a vehicular collision that killed three children and their grandfather in 2015.
[src:walden/affluenza] These pressures lead to "psychological disorders, alienation and distress", causing people to "self-medicate with mood-altering drugs and excessive alcohol consumption".
[src:walden/affluenza] They note that a number of Australians have reacted by "downshifting"—they decided to "reduce their incomes and place family, friends and contentment above money in determining their life goals".
[src:walden/affluenza] Their critique leads them to identify the need for an "alternative political philosophy", and the book concludes with a "political manifesto for wellbeing".
[src:walden/affluenza] In 2007 British pop psychologist Oliver James asserted that there was a correlation between the increasing occurrence of affluenza and the resulting increase in material inequality: the more unequal a society, the greater the unhappiness of its citizens.
[src:walden/affluenza] Referring to Vance Packard's thesis *The Hidden Persuaders* on the manipulative methods used by the advertising industry, James related the stimulation of artificial needs to the rise in affluenza.
[src:walden/affluenza] To highlight the spread of affluenza in societies with varied levels of inequality, James interviewed people in several cities including Sydney, Singapore, Auckland, Moscow, Shanghai, Copenhagen and New York.
[src:walden/affluenza] In 2008 James wrote that higher rates of mental disorders were the consequence of excessive wealth-seeking in consumerist nations.
[src:walden/affluenza] In a graph created from multiple data sources, James plotted "Prevalence of any emotional distress" and "Income inequality", attempting to show that English-speaking nations have nearly twice as much emotional distress as mainland Europe and Japan: 21.6 percent vs 11.5 percent.
[src:walden/affluenza] James defined affluenza as "placing a high value on money, possessions, appearances (physical and social) and fame", which was the rationale behind the increasing mental illness in English-speaking societies.
[src:walden/affluenza] He explained the greater incidence of affluenza as the result of 'selfish capitalism', the market liberal political governance found in English-speaking nations as compared to the less selfish capitalism pursued in mainland Europe.
[src:walden/affluenza] James asserted that societies can remove the negative consumerist effects by pursuing real needs over perceived wants, and by defining themselves as having value independent of their material possessions.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Some scholars suggest that agrarianism espouses the superiority of rural society to urban society and the independent farmer as superior to the paid worker, and sees farming as a way of life that can shape the ideal social values.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It stresses the superiority of a simpler rural life in comparison to the complexity of urban life.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The philosophical roots of agrarianism include European and Chinese philosophers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Chinese school of Agriculturalism (农家/農家) was a philosophy that advocated peasant utopian communalism and egalitarianism.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In societies influenced by Confucianism that had as its foundation that humans are innately good, the farmer was considered an esteemed productive member of society, but merchants who made money were looked down upon.
[src:walden/agrarianism] That influenced European intellectuals like François Quesnay, an avid Confucianist and advocate of China's agrarian policies, in forming the French agrarian philosophy of physiocracy.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The physiocrats, along with the ideas of John Locke and the Romantic Era, formed the basis of modern European and American agrarianism.
[src:walden/agrarianism] , du Pont advocated low tariffs and free trade.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Physiocracy (French: *physiocratie*; from the Greek for "government of nature") is an economic theory developed by a group of 18th-century Age of Enlightenment French economists.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They believed that the wealth of nations derived solely from the value of "land agriculture" or "land development" and that agricultural products should be highly priced.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Their theories originated in France and were most popular during the second half of the 18th century.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Physiocracy became one of the first well-developed theories of economics.
[src:walden/agrarianism] François Quesnay (1694–1774), the Marquis de Mirabeau (1715–1789) and Anne-Robert-Jacques Turgot (1727–1781) dominated the movement, which immediately preceded the first modern school, classical economics, which began with the publication of Adam Smith's *The Wealth of Nations* in 1776.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The physiocrats made a significant contribution in their emphasis on productive work as the source of national wealth.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This contrasted with earlier schools, in particular mercantilism, which often focused on the ruler's wealth, accumulation of gold, or the balance of trade.
[src:walden/agrarianism] For the physiocrats, however, only agricultural labor created this value in the products of society.
[src:walden/agrarianism] All "industrial" and non-agricultural labors were "unproductive appendages" to agricultural labor.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Quesnay was likely influenced by his medical training, particularly by the work of William Harvey who explained how blood flow and the circulatory system is vital to the human body; Quesnay held that the circulation of wealth was vital to the economy.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Societies at the time were also overwhelmingly agrarian.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This may be why they viewed agriculture as the primary source of a nation's wealth.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This is an idea that Quesnay purported to demonstrate with data, comparing a workshop to a farm.
[src:walden/agrarianism] He analyzed "how money flowed between the three classes of farmers, proprietors, and artisans, in the same mechanical way that blood flows between different organs" and claimed only the farm produced a surplus that added to the nation's wealth.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Physiocrats viewed the production of goods and services as equivalent to the consumption of the agricultural surplus, since human or animal muscle provided the main source of power and all energy derived from the surplus from agricultural production.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Profit in capitalist production was really only the "rent" obtained by the owner of the land on which the agricultural production took place.
[src:walden/agrarianism] "The physiocrats damned cities for their artificiality and praised what they considered to be more natural styles of living.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They celebrated farmers." They called themselves *les Économistes*, but are generally referred to as "physiocrats" to distinguish their beliefs from the many schools of economic thought that followed.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The United States president Thomas Jefferson was an agrarian who based his ideas about the budding American democracy around the notion that farmers are "the most valuable citizens" and the truest republicans.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Jefferson and his support base were committed to American republicanism, which they saw as being in opposition to monarchy, aristocracy, clericalism and corruption, and which prioritized morality and virtue, exemplified by the "yeoman farmer", "planters", and the "plain folk".
[src:walden/agrarianism] In praising the rural farmfolk, the Jeffersonians felt that financiers, bankers and industrialists created "cesspools of corruption" in the cities and should thus be avoided.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Jeffersonians sought to align the American economy more with agriculture than industry.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Part of their motive to do so was Jefferson's fear that the over-industrialization of America would create a class of wage slaves who relied on their employers for income and sustenance.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In turn, these workers would cease to be independent voters as their vote could be manipulated by said employers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] There is general agreement that the substantial United States' federal policy of offering land grants (such as thousands of gifts of land to veterans) had a positive impact on economic development in the 19th century.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Agrarian socialism is a form of agrarianism that is anti-capitalist in nature and seeks to introduce socialist economic systems in their stead.
[src:walden/agrarianism] One notable agrarian socialists was Emiliano Zapata, a leading figure in the Mexican Revolution.
[src:walden/agrarianism] As the leader of the Liberation Army of the South, his group of revolutionaries fought on behalf of the Mexican peasants, whom they saw as exploited by the landowning classes.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Zapata published the Plan of Ayala, which called for significant land reforms and land redistribution in Mexico as part of the revolution.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Zapata was killed and his forces crushed over the course of the Revolution, but his political ideas lived on in the form of Zapatismo.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Zapatismo would form the basis for neozapatismo, the ideology of the modern Zapatista Army of National Liberation.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Known as *Ejército Zapatista de Liberación Nacional* or EZLN in Spanish, EZLN is a far-left, libertarian socialist political and militant group that emerged in the state of Chiapas in southmost Mexico in 1994.
[src:walden/agrarianism] EZLN and Neozapatismo, as explicit in their name, seek to revive the agrarian socialist movement of Zapata, but fuse it with new elements such as a commitment to indigenous rights and community-level decision making.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Maoism, the far-left ideology of Mao Zedong and his followers, places a heavy emphasis on the role of peasants in its goals.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In contrast to other Marxist schools of thought which normally seek to acquire the support of urban workers, Maoism sees the peasantry as key.
[src:walden/agrarianism] During the Chinese Civil War and the Second Sino-Japanese War, Mao and the Chinese Communist Party made extensive use of peasants and rural bases in their military tactics, often eschewing the cities.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Following the eventual victory of the Communist Party in both wars, the countryside and how it should be run remained a focus for Mao.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In 1958, Mao launched the Great Leap Forward, a social and economic campaign which, amongst other things, altered many aspects of rural Chinese life.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It introduced mandatory collective farming and forced the peasantry to organize itself into communal living units which were known as people's communes.
[src:walden/agrarianism] These communes, which consisted of 5,000 people on average, were expected to meet high production quotas while the peasants who lived on them adapted to this radically new way of life.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The communes were run as co-operatives where wages and money were replaced by work points.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Peasants who criticised this new system were persecuted as "rightists" and "counter-revolutionaries".
[src:walden/agrarianism] Leaving the communes was forbidden and escaping from them was difficult or impossible, and those who attempted it were subjected to party-orchestrated "public struggle sessions," which further jeopardized their survival.
[src:walden/agrarianism] These public criticism sessions were often used to intimidate the peasants into obeying local officials and they often devolved into little more than public beatings.
[src:walden/agrarianism] On the communes, experiments were conducted in order to find new methods of planting crops, efforts were made to construct new irrigation systems on a massive scale, and the communes were all encouraged to produce steel backyard furnaces as part of an effort to increase steel production.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Similarly, the experimentation with the crops did not produce results.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In addition to this the Four Pests Campaign was launched, in which the peasants were called upon to destroy sparrows and other wild birds that ate crop seeds, in order to protect fields.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Pest birds were shot down or scared away from landing until they dropped from exhaustion.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This campaign resulted in an ecological disaster that saw an explosion of the vermin population, especially crop-eating insects, which was consequently not in danger of being killed by predators.
[src:walden/agrarianism] None of these new systems were working, but local leaders did not dare to state this, instead, they falsified reports so as not to be punished for failing to meet the quotas.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In many cases they stated that they were greatly exceeding their quotas, and in turn, the Chinese state developed a completely false sense of success with regard to the commune system.
[src:walden/agrarianism] All of this culminated in the Great Chinese Famine, which began in 1959, lasted 3 years, and saw an estimated 15 to 30 million Chinese people die.
[src:walden/agrarianism] A combination of bad weather and the new, failed farming techniques that were introduced by the state led to massive shortages of food.
[src:walden/agrarianism] By 1962, the Great Leap Forward was declared to be at an end.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Mao once again radically altered life in rural China with the launching of the Down to the Countryside Movement.
[src:walden/agrarianism] As a response to the Great Chinese Famine, the Chinese President Liu Shaoqi began "sending down" urban youths to rural China in order to recover its population losses and alleviate overcrowding in the cities.
[src:walden/agrarianism] However, Mao turned the practice into a political crusade, declaring that the sending down would strip the youth of any bourgeois tendencies by forcing them to learn from the unprivileged rural peasants.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In reality, it was the Communist Party's attempt to reign in the Red Guards, who had become uncontrollable during the course of the Cultural Revolution.
[src:walden/agrarianism] 10% of the 1970 urban population of China was sent out to remote rural villages, often in Inner Mongolia.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The villages, which were still poorly recovering from the effects of the Great Chinese Famine, did not have the excess resources that were needed to support the newcomers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Furthermore, the so-called "sent-down youth" had no agricultural experience and as a result, they were unaccustomed to the harsh lifestyle that existed in the countryside, and their unskilled labor in the villages provided little benefit to the agricultural sector.
[src:walden/agrarianism] As a result, many of the sent-down youth died in the countryside.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The relocation of the youths was originally intended to be permanent, but by the end of the Cultural Revolution, the Communist Party relented and some of those who had the capacity to return to the cities were allowed to do so.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In imitation of Mao's policies, the Khmer Rouge of Cambodia (who were heavily funded and supported by the People's Republic of China) created their own version of the Great Leap Forward which was known as "Maha Lout Ploh".
[src:walden/agrarianism] With the Great Leap Forward as its model, it had similarly disastrous effects, contributing to what is now known as the Cambodian genocide.
[src:walden/agrarianism] As a part of the Maha Lout Ploh, the Khmer Rouge sought to create an entirely agrarian socialist society by forcibly relocating 100,000 people to move from Cambodia's cities into newly created communes.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Khmer Rouge leader, Pol Pot sought to "purify" the country by setting it back to "Year Zero", freeing it from "corrupting influences".
[src:walden/agrarianism] Besides trying to completely de-urbanize Cambodia, ethnic minorities were slaughtered along with anyone else who was suspected of being a "reactionary" or a member of the "bourgeoisie", to the point that wearing glasses was seen as grounds for execution.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The killings were only brought to an end when Cambodia was invaded by the neighboring socialist nation of Vietnam, whose army toppled the Khmer Rouge.
[src:walden/agrarianism] However, with Cambodia's entire society and economy in disarray, including its agricultural sector, the country still plunged into renewed famine due to vast food shortages.
[src:walden/agrarianism] However, as international journalists began to report on the situation and send images of it out to the world, a massive international response was provoked, leading to one of the most concentrated relief efforts of its time.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Peasant parties first appeared across Eastern Europe between 1860 and 1910, when commercialized agriculture and world market forces disrupted traditional rural society, and the railway and growing literacy facilitated the work of roving organizers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Agrarian parties advocated land reforms to redistribute land on large estates among those who work it.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They also wanted village cooperatives to keep the profit from crop sales in local hands and credit institutions to underwrite needed improvements.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Many peasant parties were also nationalist parties because peasants often worked their land for the benefit of landlords of different ethnicity.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Peasant parties rarely had any power before World War I but some became influential in the interwar era, especially in Bulgaria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:walden/agrarianism] For a while, in the 1920s and the 1930s, there was a Green International (International Agrarian Bureau) based on the peasant parties in Bulgaria, Czechoslovakia, Poland, and Serbia.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It functioned primarily as an information center that spread the ideas of agrarianism and combating socialism on the left and landlords on the right and never launched any significant activities.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Bulgaria, the Bulgarian Agrarian National Union (BZNS) was organized in 1899 to resist taxes and build cooperatives.
[src:walden/agrarianism] BZNS came to power in 1919 and introduced many economic, social, and legal reforms.
[src:walden/agrarianism] However, conservative forces crushed BZNS in a 1923 coup and assassinated its leader, Aleksandar Stamboliyski (1879–1923).
[src:walden/agrarianism] BZNS was made into a communist puppet group until 1989, when it reorganized as a genuine party.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Czechoslovakia, the Republican Party of Agricultural and Smallholder People often shared power in parliament as a partner in the five-party pětka coalition.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The party's leader, Antonín Švehla (1873–1933), was prime minister several times.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It was consistently the strongest party, forming and dominating coalitions.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It moved beyond its original agrarian base to reach middle-class voters.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The party was banned by the National Front after the Second World War.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In France, the Hunting, Fishing, Nature, Tradition party is a moderate conservative, agrarian party, reaching a peak of 4.23% in the 2002 French presidential election.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It would later on become affiliated to France's main conservative party, Union for a Popular Movement.
[src:walden/agrarianism] More recently, the Resistons! movement of Jean Lassalle espoused agrarianism.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Hungary, the first major agrarian party, the small-holders party was founded in 1908.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The party became part of the government in the 1920s but lost influence in the government.
[src:walden/agrarianism] A new party, the Independent Smallholders, Agrarian Workers and Civic Party was established in 1930 with a more radical program representing larger scale land redistribution initiatives.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They implemented this program together with the other coalition parties after WWII.
[src:walden/agrarianism] However, after 1949 the party was outlawed when a one-party system was introduced.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They became part of the government again 1990–1994, and 1998–2002 after which they lost political support.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The ruling Fidesz party has an agrarian faction, and promotes agrarian interest since 2010 with the emphasis now placed on supporting larger family farms versus small-holders.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In the late 19th century, the Irish National Land League aimed to abolish landlordism in Ireland and enable tenant farmers to own the land they worked on.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The "Land War" of 1878–1909 led to the Irish Land Acts, ending absentee landlords and ground rent and redistributing land among peasant farmers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Post-independence, the Farmers' Party operated in the Irish Free State from 1922, folding into the National Centre Party in 1932.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It was mostly supported by wealthy farmers in the east of Ireland.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Clann na Talmhan (Family of the Land; also called the *National Agricultural Party*) was founded in 1938.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They focused more on the poor smallholders of the west, supporting land reclamation, afforestation, social democracy and rates reform.
[src:walden/agrarianism] They formed part of the governing coalition of the Government of the 13th Dáil and Government of the 15th Dáil.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Economic improvement in the 1960s saw farmers vote for other parties and Clann na Talmhan disbanded in 1965.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Kazakhstan, the Peasants' Union, originally a communist organization, was formed as one of first agrarian parties in independent Kazakhstan and would win four seats in the 1994 legislative election.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Agrarian Party of Kazakhstan, led by Romin Madinov, was founded in 1999, which favored the privatization of agricultural land, developments towards rural infrastructure, as well as changes in the tax system in agrarian economy.
[src:walden/agrarianism] From there, the bloc remained short-lived as it would merge with the ruling Nur Otan party in 2006.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Several other parties in Kazakhstan over the years have embraced agrarian policies in their programs in an effort to appeal towards a large rural Kazakh demographic base, which included Amanat, ADAL, and Respublica.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Since late 2000s, the Auyl party remains the largest and most influential agrarian-oriented party in Kazakhstan, as its presidential candidate Jiguli Dairabaev had become the second-place frontrunner in the 2022 presidential election after sweeping 3.4% of the vote.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In the 2023 legislative election, the Auyl party for the first time was represented the parliament after winning nine seats in the lower chamber Mäjilis.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The party raises rural issues in regard to decaying villages, rural development and the agro-industrial complex, the issues of social security of the rural population, and has consistently opposed the ongoing rural flight in Kazakhstan.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Latvia, the Union of Greens and Farmers is supportive of traditional small farms and perceives them as more environmentally friendly than large-scale farming: Nature is threatened by development, while small farms are threatened by large industrial-scale farms.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Lithuania, the government led by the Lithuanian Farmers and Greens Union was in power between 2016 and 2020.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Nordic agrarian parties, also referred to as Scandinavian agrarian parties or agrarian liberal parties, are agrarian political parties that belong to a political tradition particular to the Nordic countries.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Positioning themselves in the centre of the political spectrum, but fulfilling roles distinctive to Nordic countries, they remain hard to classify by conventional political ideology.
[src:walden/agrarianism] These parties are non-Socialist and typically combine a commitment to small businesses, rural issues and political decentralisation, and, at times, scepticism towards the European Union.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The parties have divergent views on the free market and environmentalism.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Internationally, they are most commonly aligned to the Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe (ALDE) and the Liberal International.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Historically farmers' parties, a declining farmer population after the Second World War made them broaden their scope to other issues and sections of society.
[src:walden/agrarianism] At this time three of them renamed themselves to Centre Party, with the Finnish Centre Party being the last to do so, in 1965.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In the modern period, the main agrarian parties are the Centre Party in Sweden, *Venstre* in Denmark, Centre Party in Finland, Centre Party in Norway and Progressive Party in Iceland.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Poland, the Polish People's Party (*Polskie Stronnictwo Ludowe*, PSL) traces its tradition to an agrarian party in Austro-Hungarian-controlled Galician Poland.
[src:walden/agrarianism] After the fall of the communist regime, PSL's biggest success came in 1993 elections, where it won 132 out of 460 parliamentary seats.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Since then, PSL's support has steadily declined, until 2019, when they formed Polish Coalition with an anti-establishment, direct democracy Kukiz'15 party, and managed to get 8.5% of popular vote.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Moreover, PSL tends to get much better results in local elections.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In 2014 elections they have managed to get 23.88% of votes.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The right-wing Law and Justice party has also become supportive of agrarian policies in recent years and polls show that most of their support comes from rural areas.
[src:walden/agrarianism] AGROunia resembles the features of agrarianism.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Romania, older party parties from Transylvania, Moldavia, and Wallachia merged to become the National Peasants' Party (PNȚ) in 1926.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Iuliu Maniu (1873–1953) was a prime minister with an agrarian cabinet from 1928 to 1930 and briefly in 1932–1933, but the Great Depression made proposed reforms impossible.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The communist administration dissolved the party in 1947 (along with other historical parties such as the National Liberal Party), but it reformed in 1989 after they fell from power.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The reformed party, which also incorporated elements of Christian democracy in its ideology, governed Romania as part of the Romanian Democratic Convention (CDR) between 1996 and 2000.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Serbia, Nikola Pašić (1845–1926) and his People's Radical Party dominated Serbian politics after 1903.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The party also monopolized power in Yugoslavia from 1918 to 1929.
[src:walden/agrarianism] During the dictatorship of the 1930s, the prime minister was from that party.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In Ukraine, the Radical Party of Oleh Lyashko has promised to purify the country of oligarchs "with a pitchfork".
[src:walden/agrarianism] In land law the heyday of English, Irish (and thus Welsh) agrarianism was c.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The heyday was eroded by hundreds of Acts of Parliament to expressly permit enclosure, chiefly from 1650 to the 1810s.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Politicians standing strongly as reactionaries to this included the Levellers, those anti-industrialists (Luddites) going beyond opposing new weaving technology and, later, radicals such as William Cobbett.
[src:walden/agrarianism] A high level of net national or local self-sufficiency has a strong base in campaigns and movements.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In the 19th century such empowered advocates included Peelites and most Conservatives.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The 21st century has seen decarbonisation already in electricity markets.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Following protests and charitable lobbying local food has seen growing market share, sometimes backed by wording in public policy papers and manifestos.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The UK has many sustainability-prioritising businesses, green charity campaigns, events and lobby groups ranging from espousing allotment gardens (hobby community farming) through to a clear policy of local food and/or self-sustainability models.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The National Party of Australia (formerly called the Country Party), from the 1920s to the 1970s, promulgated its version of agrarianism, which it called "countrymindedness".
[src:walden/agrarianism] The goal was to enhance the status of the graziers (operators of big sheep stations) and small farmers and justified subsidies for them.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The New Zealand Liberal Party aggressively promoted agrarianism in its heyday (1891–1912).
[src:walden/agrarianism] The landed gentry and aristocracy ruled Britain at this time.
[src:walden/agrarianism] New Zealand never had an aristocracy but its wealthy landowners largely controlled politics before 1891.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Liberal Party set out to change that by a policy it called "populism." Richard Seddon had proclaimed the goal as early as 1884: "It is the rich and the poor; it is the wealthy and the landowners against the middle and labouring classes.
[src:walden/agrarianism] That, Sir, shows the real political position of New Zealand." The Liberal strategy was to create a large class of small landowning farmers who supported Liberal ideals.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Liberal government also established the basis of the later welfare state such as old age pensions and developed a system for settling industrial disputes, which was accepted by both employers and trade unions.
[src:walden/agrarianism] In 1893, it extended voting rights to women, making New Zealand the first country in the world to do so.
[src:walden/agrarianism] To obtain land for farmers, the Liberal government from 1891 to 1911 purchased 3,100,000 acres (1,300,000 ha) of Maori land.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The government also purchased 1,300,000 acres (530,000 ha) from large estate holders for subdivision and closer settlement by small farmers.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Advances to Settlers Act (1894) provided low-interest mortgages, and the agriculture department disseminated information on the best farming methods.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Liberals proclaimed success in forging an egalitarian, anti-monopoly land policy.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The policy built up support for the Liberal Party in rural North Island electorates.
[src:walden/agrarianism] By 1903, the Liberals were so dominant that there was no longer an organized opposition in Parliament.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The United States and Canada both saw a rise of Agrarian-oriented parties in the early twentieth century as economic troubles motivated farming communities to become politically active.
[src:walden/agrarianism] It has been proposed that different responses to agrarian protest largely determined the course of power generated by these newly energized rural factions.
[src:walden/agrarianism] These reactions may have helped determine the outcome of agrarian power and political associations in the US and Canada.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Economic desperation experienced by farmers across the state of Kansas in the nineteenth century spurred the creation of The People's Party in 1890, and soon-after would gain control of the governor's office in 1892.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This party, consisting of a mix of Democrats, Socialists, Populists, and Fusionists, would find itself buckling from internal conflict regarding the unlimited coinage of silver.
[src:walden/agrarianism] The Populists permanently lost power in 1898.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Oklahoma farmers considered their political activity during the early twentieth century due to the outbreak of war, depressed crop prices, and an inhibited sense of progression towards owning their own farms.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Tenancy had been reportedly as high as 55% in Oklahoma by 1910.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This agrarian-backed Socialist party would win numerous offices, causing a panic within the local Democratic party.
[src:walden/agrarianism] This agrarian-Socialist movement would be inhibited by voter suppression laws aimed at reducing the participation of voters of color, as well as national wartime policies intended to disrupt political elements considered subversive.
[src:walden/agrarianism] During the 1930s and 1940s many farmers supported the Wisconsin Progressive Party - National Progressives.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Agrarianism during this time was often linked with progressive politics.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Agrarianism is similar to but not identical with the back-to-the-land movement.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Agrarianism concentrates on the fundamental goods of the earth, on communities of more limited economic and political scale than in modern society, and on simple living, even when the shift involves questioning the "progressive" character of some recent social and economic developments.
[src:walden/agrarianism] Thus, agrarianism is not industrial farming, with its specialization on products and industrial scale.
[src:walden/axs-company] The initial AXS deployment was August 2011 and venues and services have been added in a phased roll out.
[src:walden/axs-company] As of August 2013, AXS was the exclusive or primary ticket provider for over 30 US venues and nine UK venues.
[src:walden/axs-company] The first Crypto.com Arena concert available only through AXS was Beyoncé in 2013.
[src:walden/axs-company] Although the NBA's Los Angeles Lakers still use Ticketmaster primarily for the majority of tickets, the premium sections in the arena use AXS for Laker games.
[src:walden/axs-company] The Los Angeles Kings of the NHL use AXS for all ticket types, including parking at the arena.
[src:walden/axs-company] The white-label technology Outbox developed enables AEG to sell tickets under either the AXS brand name or under local venue name brands, which have considerable local support, while providing centralized CRM services for either approach.
[src:walden/axs-company] It was developed and is operated by Anschutz Entertainment Group (AEG) in partnership with Outbox Technology.
[src:walden/axs-company] In September 2019, AEG bought out Outbox's partnership and AXS is now a wholly owned subsidiary of AEG.
[src:walden/axs-company] In January 2014, AEG announced that AXS had purchased Examiner.com, a user-generated news site, in order to leverage the site's entertainment content.
[src:walden/axs-company] In 2015, AXS merged with the paperless ticketing system Veritix.
[src:walden/axs-company] The combined entity then generated more than $2 billion in annual transactions.
[src:walden/axs-company] AEG's partner for eight years, Outbox, developed of the white-label ticket selling technology.
[src:walden/axs-company] Founded in 2005 by husband and wife Jean-Francoys Brousseau and Constance Raymond, Outbox also counted the Cirque du Soleil among its shareholders.
[src:walden/axs-company] After gaining experience with its technology worldwide, in 2011 Outbox created a partnership with AEG, and AXS was born.
[src:walden/axs-company] Their ticket selling system allows all live entertainment venues to control their inventory, pricing, and consumer data without third-party involvement.
[src:walden/axs-company] In 2019, Outbox sold its stake in AXS to AEG.
[src:walden/axs-company] AXS aims to block large-volume, automated purchases by computer programs used by ticket resellers by using a "waiting room" facility on a separate server.
[src:walden/axs-company] Users log their personal details and purchase information prior to tickets going on sale and are screened for multiple purchases.
[src:walden/axs-company] AXS selectively offers an add-on feature, AXS Invite, which lets ticket purchasers reserve adjacent seats for friends, who have up to 48 hours to decide on receiving email or social-media notification.
[src:walden/axs-company] Invite is not available when tickets are initially sold, is only available at some venues, and is unlikely to help at oversubscribed shows.
[src:walden/axs-company] AXS acknowledges that the feature is "really about finding a way to sell more tickets", while enhancing customer convenience.
[src:walden/axs-company] Carbonhouse, a web design agency with over 400 clients worldwide, was acquired by AEG.
[src:walden/axs-company] This will allow integration of additional features into the AXS ticketing platform.
[src:walden/axs-company] AEG had a partnership with StubHub, a secondary ticketing service, to place tickets from StubHub in AXS ticket listings.
[src:walden/axs-company] This Partnership ended in 2018 when AXS Mobile ID technology and the “FanSight” purchase experience technology will be integrated in 30 of AEG's U.S. venues.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau makes precise scientific observations of nature as well as metaphorical and poetic uses of natural phenomena.
[src:walden/walden] There has been much speculation as to why Thoreau went to live at the pond in the first place.
[src:walden/walden] Although Thoreau went to Walden to escape what he considered "over-civilization", and in search of the "raw" and "savage delight" of the wilderness, he also spent considerable amounts of his time reading and writing.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau used his time at Walden Pond (July 4, 1845 – September 6, 1847) to write his first book, *A Week on the Concord and Merrimack Rivers* (1849).
[src:walden/walden] The experience later inspired *Walden*, in which Thoreau compresses the time into a single calendar year and uses passages of four seasons to symbolize human development.
[src:walden/walden] By immersing himself in nature, Thoreau hoped to gain a more objective understanding of society through introspection.
[src:walden/walden] Simple living and self-sufficiency were Thoreau's other goals.
[src:walden/walden] The whole project was inspired by transcendentalist philosophy, a central theme of the American Romantic Period.
[src:walden/walden] Part memoir and part spiritual quest, *Walden* opens with the announcement that Thoreau spent two years at Walden Pond living a simple life without support of any kind.
[src:walden/walden] Readers are reminded that at the time of publication, Thoreau has returned to living among the civilized.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau carefully recounts his time in the woods through his writing in *Walden*.
[src:walden/walden] Critics have thoroughly analyzed the different writing styles that Thoreau uses.
[src:walden/walden] Critic Nicholas Bagnall writes that Thoreau's observations of nature are "lyrical" and "exact".
[src:walden/walden] Another critic, Henry Golemba, asserts that the writing style of *Walden* is very natural.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau employs various styles of writing where his words are both intricate and simple at the same time.
[src:walden/walden] For instance, when Thoreau describes the silence of nature, the reader may feel that serene moment as well.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau continues to connect back to nature throughout the book because he wants to depict what he experienced and saw.
[src:walden/walden] Many scholars have compared Thoreau to fellow transcendentalist writer Ralph Waldo Emerson.
[src:walden/walden] Although Emerson was 14 years his senior, much of Thoreau's writing was influenced by Emerson.
[src:walden/walden] Critic John Brooks Moore examined the relationship between Thoreau and Emerson and the effects it had on their respective works.
[src:walden/walden] Moore claims that Thoreau did not simply mimic Emerson's work, but he was actually the more dominant one in the relationship.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau has learned from Emerson and some "Emersonism" can be found in his works, but Thoreau's work is distinct from Emerson's.
[src:walden/walden] Many critics have also seen the influence of Thomas Carlyle (a great influence on Emerson), particularly in Thoreau's use of an extended clothing metaphor, which Carlyle had used in *Sartor Resartus* (1831).
[src:walden/walden] Scholars have recognized *Walden*'s use of biblical allusions.
[src:walden/walden] Such allusions are useful tools to convince readers because the Bible is seen as a principal book of truth.
[src:walden/walden] According to scholar Judith Saunders, the signature biblical allusion identified in the book is, "Walden was dead and is alive again." This is almost verbatim from Luke 15.11–32.
[src:walden/walden] Thoreau is personifying Walden Pond to further the story relevant to the Bible.
[src:walden/walden] He compares the process of death and rebirth of the pond to self-transformation in humans.
[src:walden/walden] It is often assumed that critics initially ignored *Walden*, and that those who reviewed the book were evenly split or slightly more negative than positive in their assessment of it.
[src:walden/walden] But, researchers have shown that *Walden* actually was "more favorably and widely received by Thoreau's contemporaries than hitherto suspected".
[src:walden/walden] Of the 66 initial reviews that have been found so far, 46 "were strongly favorable".
[src:walden/walden] Some reviews were rather superficial, merely recommending the book or predicting its success with the public; others were more lengthy, detailed, and nuanced with both positive and negative comments.
[src:walden/walden] Positive comments included praise for Thoreau's independence, practicality, wisdom, "manly simplicity", and fearlessness.
[src:walden/walden] On the other hand, the terms "quaint" or "eccentric" appeared in over half of the book's initial reviews.
[src:walden/walden] Other terms critical of Thoreau included selfish, strange, impractical, privileged (or "manor born"), and misanthropic.
[src:walden/walden] One review compared and contrasted Thoreau's form of living to communism, probably not in the sense of Marxism, but instead of communal living or religious communism.
[src:walden/walden] While valuing freedom from possessions, Thoreau was not communal in the sense of practicing sharing or of embracing community.
[src:walden/walden] So, communism "is better than our hermit's method of getting rid of encumbrance".
[src:walden/walden] Poet John Greenleaf Whittier criticized what he perceived as the message in *Walden* that man should lower himself to the level of a woodchuck and walk on four legs.
[src:walden/walden] He said: "Thoreau's *Walden* is a capital reading, but very wicked and heathenish ...
[src:walden/walden] After all, for me, I prefer walking on two legs".
[src:walden/walden] Author Edward Abbey criticized Thoreau's ideas and experiences at Walden in detail throughout his response to *Walden* called "Down the River with Thoreau", written in 1980.
[src:walden/walden] Today, despite these criticisms, *Walden* stands as one of America's most celebrated works of literature.
[src:walden/walden] Skinner wrote that he carried a copy of *Walden* with him in his youth, and eventually wrote *Walden Two* in 1945, a fictional utopia about 1,000 members who live together in a Thoreau-inspired community.
[src:walden/walden] Kathryn Schulz has accused Thoreau of hypocrisy, misanthropy and being sanctimonious based on his writings in *Walden*, although this criticism has been perceived as highly selective.
[src:walden/walden] The game production was also supported by grants from the National Endowment for the Humanities and was part of the Sundance New Frontier Story Lab in 2014.
[src:walden/walden] The game was released to critical acclaim on July 4, 2017, celebrating both the day that Thoreau went down to the pond to begin his experiment and the 200th anniversary of Thoreau's birth.
[src:walden/walden] It was nominated for the Off-Broadway Award for Best Indie Game at the New York Game Awards 2018.
[src:walden/walden] Ultimately, the project will provide a space for readers to discuss Thoreau in the margins of his texts.
